  {
    "index": 3,
    "hash": "0tgZw49Vf8xuiGJ8Ds46tMWIVuY=",
    "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:30.000Z",
    "action": {
      "type": "SET_CONTENT",
      "input": {
        "content": "## Setup sequence\n\n`createSwarmSyncBuilder(logger, jwtHandler)` returns `{ syncBuilder, compositeFactory, registerGqlFactory }`:\n\n1. `CompositeChannelFactory` created with `\"swarm\"` registered.\n2. `SyncBuilder.withChannelFactory(compositeFactory)`.\n\nThen wired into the reactor:\n\n```\nReactorBuilder\n  .withSync(syncBuilder)       // proper builder API\n  .withJwtHandler(jwtHandler)\n```\n\n`buildModule()` runs:\n- Creates queue with the document-model resolver.\n- `SyncManager.startup()` recreates persisted remotes.\n- Swarm remotes work immediately because the factory is already registered.\n\nAfter `buildModule()`: `registerGqlFactory(reactorModule.queue)` registers `\"gql\"` on the same `CompositeChannelFactory`, so GQL remotes can now be added via `addRemoteDrive()`.\n\n## Dispatch\n\n```\ncompositeFactory.instance(config)\n  config.type === \"gql\"   -> GqlRequestChannelFactory -> GqlRequestChannel\n  config.type === \"swarm\" -> SwarmChannelFactory    -> SwarmChannel\n```\n\nSyncManager remains channel-type-agnostic; it only touches `outbox`, `inbox`, and `deadLetter` on whatever channel object it receives.",
        "updatedAt": "2026-05-13T13:00:30.000Z"
      },
      "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:30.000Z"
    }
  },
